Notes: None

Name: Mt. Brighton

Name: Banff townsite
Notes: Trails: Three trails on the south side of the town of Banff have a combined total of 33 km of trails groomed for cross-country skiing.Sundance trail (groomed rated Easy) runs 4 km along the Bow River then gently ascends to Sundance Canyon. It also connects to the Brewster Creek trail leading to Sundance Lodge.Spray River Loop (groomed rated Easy to Moderate) runs 12.5 km from Bow Falls along both sides of Spray River.The Goat Creek trail (groomed rated Moderate) continues from the far end of the Spray River Loop to a trailhead on Spray Lakes Road in Kananaskis Country. It's mainly uphill from Banff and a total distance of 19 km one way so its best to get dropped off on Spray Lake Road and ski to Banff if possible.There are also several backcountry trails including the Rundle Riverside trail extending 16 km to Canmore Nordic Centre.CAUTION: In backcountry areas there may be a possibility of avalanches check the park's avalanche bulletin before heading out and follow the proper avalanche safety guidelines.
Google-address: Banff townsite, Banff AB

Name: Sundance Trails
Notes: Trails: Brewster Creek Trail is a 11 km linear trail that leads to the Sundance backcountry lodge. The groomed cross-country ski trail is rated Moderate. In addition there are about another 40 km of backcountry trails in the region.CAUTION: In backcountry areas there may be a possibility of avalanche check the park's avalanche bulletin before heading out and follow the proper avalanche safety guidelines.
Google-address: Sundance Trails, Banff AB

Name: Lake Minnewanka/Cascade
Notes: Trails: A very popular trail in Banff National Park is the Cascade Trail at Lake Minnewanka which is a linear groomed trail (14 km each way). The trail is rated Easy and crosses the Cascade River near its midpoint.CAUTION: In backcountry areas there may be a possibility of avalanches check the park's avalanche bulletin before heading out and follow the proper avalanche safety guidelines.
Google-address: Lake Minnewanka/Cascade, Banff AB

Name: Castle Junction

Castle Junction trail is 9 km one way. Red Earth Creek trail is 12 km one way. Shadow Lake Lodge (open weekends Feb-Mar) is another 3 km past the end of the groomed trail. There are also several backcountry trails.CAUTION: In backcountry areas there may be a possibility of avalanche check the park's avalanche bulletin before heading out and follow the proper avalanche safety guidelines.
Google-address: Castle Junction, Banff AB

Name: Lake Louise

Trails link the lake and town of Lake Louise and extend north and south including one that goes 10 km to the Great Divide and Yoho National Park.On the east side of the highway the Pipestone network provides another 20 km of ski trails. Most of the groomed trails in the Lake Louise area are rated Novice Easy and Moderate. Approximately 20 km are groomed for both classic and skate.CAUTION: In backcountry areas there may be a possibility of avalanche check the park's avalanche bulletin before heading out and follow the proper avalanche safety guidelines.

Name: Whistler Ski Trails
Notes: Trails: In the town of Whistler 32 km of trails are groomed for cross-country skiing (classic and skate) in Lost Lake Park and on two golf courses. Four km of trails are lighted for night skiing. Many other areas nearby are suitable for backcountry touring and telemarking but check the avalanche conditions before setting out.Two other nearby ski areas are Callaghan Country and the Whistler Olympic Park site of the nordic ski events for the 2010 Olympic Winter Games.
Google-address: Whistler Ski Trails, Whistler BC

Name: Callaghan Country
Notes: Trails: Callaghan Country is a luxurious full-service backcountry lodge with 40 km of trails groomed for cross-country skiing. The trails connect with those of the Whistler Olympic Park site of the nordic events for the 2010 Olympic Winter Games. Day skiers can purchase a combined pass good for both trail systems which together offer a total of more than 90 km of trails.Callaghan Country has lots of singletrack trails and some double track and skating. There are some difficult sections of trails lots of intermediate sections and some easy sections.The surrounding Coast Mountain Range provides lots of opportunities for backcountry touring and telemarking. Guided backcountry trips can be arranged through the lodge.CAUTION: Anyone planning on backcountry trips should be knowledgeable and experienced in backcountry travel and avalanche safety.
Google-address: Callaghan Country, Whistler BC

Name: Whistler Olympic Park
Notes: Trails: Whistler Olympic Park the venue for the 2010 Olympic nordic competitions offers 55 km of groomed trails. The park's trails connect with those of Callaghan Country and together they offer a total of more than 90 km of groomed trails.The competition trails for cross-country skiing and biathlon together with additional recreational trails provide 11 beginner trails 12 intermediate and four expert trails. Six km of trails are lighted for night skiing one evening a week and there are 5 km of rollerski trails during the summer.The Whistler Olympic Park operates from mid-November to mid-April when snow conditions permit. Before planning your trip check the park's event calendar to see if the trails will be closed for an event. BC's largest loppet the P'ayakentsut is held here in February.
Google-address: Whistler Olympic Park, Whistler BC

Name: Mt Washington Resort

Backcountry skiing in Strathcona Provincial Park is possible but check avalanche conditions before heading out.Mount Washington Resort is the site of the Vancouver Island Loppet in March.

Name: Hemlock Valley Ski Resort

Name: Norman Wells Cross Country Ski Club

There are also about 15 km of backcountry trails.Remarks by the club president (2004): Most of the trails are marked but we are still improving them so expect the unexpected. A wolf fox wolverine or some two legged creature may have knock over a sign but look for the ski tracks.We live and play in an isolated remote northern Canadian wilderness region (Latitude 65 degrees) where common sense must prevail. Limited sun light cold weather and sudden changes in weather are extreme hazards. When you travel the ski trails connecting multi-use trails and back country make sure to let someone know where exactly you are headed and your expected time of return. There are no patrols of the ski trails multi-use trails or back country so if you get yourself into trouble you are on your own!

Name: Club de ski de fond Labelle
Notes: Trails: Approximately 25 km of trails are groomed for cross-country skiing by the Club de ski de fond Labelle. Five trails are rated Easy nine Intermediate and five Difficult.

Name: Saint-Jovite
Notes: Trails: Approximately 45 km of trails groomed for cross-country skiing (including some with skating lanes) wend their way around the Mont-Tremblant resort and south towards the town of Saint-Jovite. Several backcountry trails traverse the region.Trails at Domaine St Bernard are situated in a more natural setting than the other trails through the town and resort. Roughly half the trails are rated Easy 40% Difficult and 10% Most Difficult.
Google-address: Saint-Jovite, St-Jovite QC

Name: Parc du Mont Tremblant
Notes: Trails: In the western sector of Parc du Mont Tremblant (La Diable) near Lac Monroe 55 km of trails are groomed for cross-country skiing including 13 km for skating technique. There are also a network of backcountry trails that connect with Pimbina in the eastern sector of the park. Backcountry huts are available for rent from the park.Six trails are rated Easy two Intermediate and three Difficult. New in 2012: a 13 km loop connects to the Chutes-Croches waterfall.
Google-address: Parc du Mont Tremblant, Lac-Superieur QC

Name: Base de plein air Le Petit Bonheur
Notes: Trails: At Le P'tit Bonheur outdoor recreation centre 45 km of trails are groomed for cross-country skiing. The trails are open to the public on weekends only.
Google-address: Base de plein air Le Petit Bonheur, Lac-Superieur QC

Name: Parc des campeurs
Notes: Trails: At Parc des campeurs 45 km of trails are groomed for cross-country skiing (classic only). A trail connects with Saint-Adolphe 15 km to the south.
Google-address: Parc des campeurs, Sainte-Agathe QC

Name: Centre de ski de fond l'Estrel
Notes: Trails: Near the town of Esterel 35 km of cross-country ski trails are groomed for both classic and skating. Of the 10 groomed trails three are rated Easy three Intermediate and four Difficult. Most of the trails are uni-directional so be sure to ski in the direction indicated. There are also some trails for backcountry skiing. In 2009 operation of the trails changed from Esterel resort to Hors Limite Inc. and the center moved to its present location.
Google-address: Centre de ski de fond l'Estrel, Esterel QC

Name: Parc du Mont-Tremblant
Notes: Trails: The east sector of Parc du Mont-Tremblant (La Pimbina) offers about 50 km of ungroomed trails for cross-country skiing. The park's backcountry trails connect with La Diable (#24) in the western sector of the park to offer a total of more than 100 km of ski touring. Several backcountry huts are available for rent from the park.
Google-address: Parc du Mont-Tremblant, Saint-Donat QC

Name: La Reserve/Saint-Donat
Notes: Trails: About 32 km of trails are available for cross-country skiing in St-Donat and at La Reserve resort. The trails are maintained by La Reserve resort and the Club plein air de Saint-Donat. A backcountry trail connects with l'Interval.
Google-address: La Reserve/Saint-Donat, Saint-Donat QC

Name: Forat Ouareau
Notes: Trails: Foret Ouareau offers 29 km of trails that are groomed for cross-country skiing. Another 26 km of backcountry skiing on the Sentier National (National Trail) traversing several peaks is best suited to snowshoeing.
Google-address: Forat Ouareau, Notre-Dame-de-la-Merci QC

Name: Club de ski de fond d'Evian
Notes: Trails: About 30 km of trails are groomed for cross-country skiing by the Club de ski de fond d'Evain. A new chalet was opened in 2007. Six trails are rated Easy four Difficult and three Very Difficult.
Google-address: 450 Avenue de l'Église, Rouyn-Noranda, QC J0Z 1Y0, Canada

Name: Base de plein air l'Interval
Notes: Trails: L'Interval outdoor centre offers 30 km of backcountry trails including a trail up Mt Kaikop one of the highest peaks in the region. A 10 km trail is groomed for cross-country skiing.
Google-address: Base de plein air l'Interval, Sainte-Lucie-des-Larentides QC

Name: Centre de Ski de Fond Val-David
Notes: Trails: Val-David and Far Hills have a combined total of 63 km of trails groomed for cross-country skiing including 12 km for skating. The trails connect with the P'tit Train du Nord linear park. There are also several backcountry trails one of which was blazed by the legendary Jackrabbit Johannsen.In 2005 a land dispute involving trails in the Val-David and Val-Morin region resulted in the creation of the 500-hectare Parc Dufresne encompassing many of the Far Hills and Val-David trails.
Google-address: Centre de Ski de Fond Val-David, Val-David QC

Name: Centre de plein air Sainte-Adele
Notes: Trails: At Sainte-Adele more than 40 km of of trails are available for cross-country skiing in two different locations: Mont-Rolland to the south and Loup Garou to the north near Chantecler. Most of the south trails are rated Very Difficult. Five groomed trails in the north sector provide 20 km of Intermdiate skiing.
Google-address: Centre de plein air Sainte-Adele, Sainte-Adele QC

Name: St-Adolphe-d'Howard
Notes: Trails: At St-Adolphe-d'Howard 30 km of trails are groomed for classic technique. Another 50 km of backcountry trails are located around the town. A trail connects with Parc des Campeurs 15 km to the north. An ungroomed trail links with the Morin Heights backcountry trails. Most of the trails are rated intermediate to advanced.
Google-address: St-Adolphe-d'Howard, St-Adolphe-d'Howard QC

Name: Viking Ski Club
Notes: Trails: Viking Ski Club grooms 50 km of trails for cross-country skiing including 10 km of racing trails with a lane for skating. Two sections of the trail are rated Easy two are Difficult and one is Most Difficult but most trails have both hilly and flat sections. The Viking trail system connects with those of Morin Heights. The club hosts the Morin-Heights Viking Loppet in late February.
Google-address: Viking Ski Club, Morin-Heights QC

Name: Morin Heights
Notes: Trails: The cross-country ski centre operated by the municipality of Morin-Heights offers 60 km of groomed trails plus there is also many backcountry trails. Two trails are rated Easy ten are Difficult and ten Most Difficult. Except for the Aerobic Corridor the trails are single-track with a recommended direction of travel.The groomed Norin Heights trails connect with those of the Viking Club. Backcountry trails connect with Saint-Adolphe 10 km north.
Google-address: Morin Heights, Morin-Heights QC

Name: Centre de ski de fond La Randonnee
Notes: Trails: Brownsburg's Centre de ski de fond La Randonnee groom 24 km of trails for cross-country skiing (classic only) all rated Intermediate. The centre is open Wednesday to Sunday.
Google-address: Centre de ski de fond La Randonnee, Brownsburg QC

Name: Lac Carling
Notes: Trails: About 20 km of trails are available for cross-country skiing at the five-star Lac Carling resort.
Google-address: Lac Carling, Pine Hill QC

Name: Club de Montagne d'Argenteuil
Notes: Trails: Closed in 1999--no longer operates

Name: Centre de ski de fond Gai-Luron
Notes: Trails: Centre de ski de fond Gai Luron grooms 24 km of trails for cross-country skiing (classic technique). Four km of trails are rated Beginner 8 km are Intermediate and 12 km are Expert.

Name: Club de ski de fond Mt Rolland

Name: Parc lineaire le P'tit Train du Nord
Notes: Trails: The 45 km section of the P'tit Train du Nord rail trail from Saint-Jerome to Val-David is groomed for cross-country skiing (classic and skating technique). North of Val-David the trail is for snowmobiling only. The linear park links up with trails at the Riviere-du-Nord regional park Sainte-Adele and Val-David/Far-Hills. The trail rises gradually from St-Jerome to Val-David. Due to its even surface the trail does not require much snow to be skiable so has generally a longer ski season than the other nearby centres.
Google-address: Parc lineaire le P'tit Train du Nord, Val-David QC

Name: Club de ski de fond de Granada
Notes: Trails: About 16 km of trails are groomed for cross-country skiing by the Granada ski club. Trails range from easy to intermediate.

Name: Parc regional de la Riviere-du-Nord
Notes: Trails: At the Parc regional de la Riviere-du-Nord there are 25 km of trails that are groomed for cross-country skiing including 5 km for skating technique. Most of the trails are rated Easy or Intermediate. The trails connect with the P'tit Train du Nord linear park.
Google-address: Parc regional de la Riviere-du-Nord, Saint-Jerome QC

Name: Parc du Domaine Vert

Name: Parc d'Oka
Notes: Trails: Parc d'Oka grooms 47 km of trails for cross-country skiing including 23 km for skating technique. Trails consist of easy lakeside loops and more challenging hillside trails. Twenty-seven km of trails are rated Easy 7 km are More Difficult and 16 km Most Difficult.A viewpoint at the top of the Calvaire hill overlooks Lac des Deux Montagnes. Seven stucco structures situated at the viewpoint and along the Calvaire trail house religious frescoes. A 4 km trail is lighted for night skiing on certain evenings.
Google-address: Parc d'Oka, Oka QC

Name: Centre de plein air des Cedres

Name: L'Escapade Linear Park
Notes: Trails: L'Escapde Linear Park in Rigaud has 25 km of cross-country ski trails through predominantly maple forest groomed by the city of Rigaud. The trails consist of three long loops with a few linear offshoots. Situated on Mont Rigaud half the trails are rated Difficult. From the upper trails there a viewpoints overlooking the St Lawrence valley and the Adirondacks.
Google-address: L'Escapade Linear Park, Rigaud QC

Name: Parc du Cap St Jacques

Name: Parc du Mont-Royal
Notes: Trails: Montreal's Mount Royal Park offers about 18 km of trails groomed for cross-country skiing in the heart of the city. Trails are groomed for classic except for two separate skating trails, one at Beaver Lake and the other near Avenue Parc.The two loop trails around the summit of the mountain are one-way (clockwise) so make sure that you are going in the right direction. The summit trails are the most challenging on the island best suited to intermediate skiers. Other Montreal city parks that have easy ski trails include Maisonneuve and Angrignon parks with about 10 km each.
Google-address: Parc du Mont-Royal, Montreal QC

Google-address: Club de ski de fond Nordic, Saint-Bruno-de-Montarville QC

Name: Parc de la Gatineau

The 363 square km park north of Ottawa is operated by the National Capital Commission and is probably the largest groomed ski trail network in Canada.Trails are patrolled by professionals seven days a week aided by volunteers on weekends. Emergency phones are located at eight spots in the park.In February the Gatineau Loppet (formerly the Keskinada Loppet) one of 15 Worldloppets held each year attracts more than 3000 skiers in one of Canada's biggest cross-country skiing event. A free guided nature interpretation snowshoe tour is offered once a week.

Name: Pine Haven Recreation Area
Notes: One of the Midland County Parks, Pine Haven is located in the woods along US10 near Sanford. Take the West River Road exit from US10 and follow the signs to the park. Trails (about 15K) are sometimes groomed (more reliably for classic). The upper-level beginner's loop is very flat, while several intermediate and advanced loops descend from the plateau to two small streams. No rentals or food, but there is a porta-john and often a ski patrol on weekends. No lighted trails.
Google-address: Pine Haven Recreation Area , Midland, MI

Name: Addison Oaks
Notes: Addison Oaks is another Oakland County park north of Rochester that usually is groomed for both skating and classic. Last year (2001-2002) they didn't groom at all. I think because of lack of snow but it might have been budgetary. Addison has a great trail network, quite a bit of single track in the woods and a lot along open farm fields but in the shadow of tree lines to preserve snow. It's the same course they run Mt. Bike races on in the spring and fall (race coming up Sept. 15, 2002) I'll find out what the situation with grooming is there and let you know what they'll have this year. (By Michael Bliss)
Google-address: Addison Oaks, 1480 West Romeo Road, Lake Orion, MI

Name: Independence Oaks
Notes: 10 minutes north of Pontiac, S.E. Michigan's best kept secret. Independence Oaks, an Oakland County Park, is accessible from I-75. Take exit 89, Sashabaw rd. North 3 miles entrance on your left. This park gets snow when everywhere else gets just a dusting. 6-8 week season plus, up to 3 months of skiing. Park maintenance grooms for skating and lays a track for classic. Warming hut and old classic rentals. Vending machines. Closes at dark. $5.00/day pass (Oakland Country residents, $8 everyone else), $20.00 for annual. Awesome hilly trails make you feel like your up north. You'll not believe your an hour from Detroit. Park service people though enthusiastic are not knowledgeable about trail conditions. They'll tell you no skiing when it's great back in the woods. (By Michael Bliss)
Google-address: Independence Oaks, 9501 Sashabaw Road, Pontiac, MI

Quite a few skiers use this area throughout the winter. It has 18 fairways with nice rolling terrain. The grass they have planted there allows the snow to sit on top and it lasts pretty long even when it gets over 32f. We have been bugging the owner to groom a loop trail with no luck...so far. -Kevin Kelly.
Google-address: Dune's Golf Course, 6464 W. Empire Hwy (M-72), Empire, MI

Name: Muskegon Winter Sports Complex
Notes:
There are two artificially lighted cross country ski trails with lengths of 2.5 kilometers and 5.0 kilometers respectively; a 3.5 kilometer expert trail; and, a 4.0 kilometer "natural classical" only trail.Trails are groomed daily for both classical and skate skiing. 
 
 The trail winds through dense forests dominated by white pines which have often referred to as the "enchanted forest" after a snowfall. The "quiet" skier often encounters local wildlife, such as whitetail deer, ruffled grouse, squirrel, or the growing population of wild turkey.

Name: Rikert Nordic Center
Notes:
From their homepage: "55+ km of skate and classic skiing, snowshoeing and fat biking nestled in the heart of the Green Mountain National Forest.
 Our trails lead through wonderful forests, old farm fields edged by stonewalls, along babbling brooks, and even past Robert Frost’s Summer Cabin. You’ll quickly understand the inspiration this area has offered to so many.
 The Nordic Center is fully ADA accessible, offers a full service rental shop, and a PSIA certified ski school. Relax and refuel by the warm wood stove, enjoy the great food, warm beverages and a cozy atmosphere."

Google-address: 1820 Edgcumbe Rd, St Paul, MN 55116, USA

Name: Grass Lake
Notes: Part of the Vadnais-Snail Lakes Park these trails have both wooded and marsh land characteristics. Easy to intermediate level of difficulty.

Name: Tamarack Nature Center
Notes: Ski through beautiful prairie woodland and marsh with abundant wildlife. 1km practice loop. Easy to intermediate level of difficulty. Visitor center with ski rental.

Name: Como Golf Course
Notes: Trails are on the golf course. Some nice hills but most of the course is pretty exposed. There is one back leg that is quite shaded and seems to hold snow long after the rest of the course loses it. Rentals at the chalet.

Name: Pine Lake Ski Trails
Notes: Located in the Tamarac National Wildlife Refuge.
Google-address: Co Hwy 29, Rochert, MN 56578, USA

Name: Frontenac State Park
Notes: Trails rated easy to challenging.
Google-address: 34661 County 2 Blvd, Frontenac, MN 55026, USA

Name: Nerstrand-Big Woods State Park
Notes: All 6 miles of trail run through the Big Woods Landscape with portions along Prairie Creek and Hidden Falls waterfall. Park manager recommends skiers walk the short portion of difficult terrain down Hidden Falls Trail to access the intermediate to easy rolling terrain.

Name: Sibley State Park
Notes: Intermediate to challenging trails with lots of ups and downs. Double tracked predominantly one-way loop trails. Skate ski from park office to Mt. Tom for a spectacular winter panoramic view of the area.

Name: Flandrau State Park

Name: Mississippi National Ski Trails
Notes: 8KM groomed for classic 7KM groomed for both classic and skating. The classic loop is one through wooded terrain and offers extensive views of the Mississippi River. The trailhead is located at the Mississippi National Golf Course Parking lot 2 miles south of Red Wing. Also known as Red Wing East End Recreational Area.
Google-address: 28326 US-61, Red Wing, MN 55066, USA

Name: Chester Woods Park
Notes: This is a county park that contains 1300 acres. They groom about 5 miles of trails. The park is both wooded and hilly and the trails are well marked with maps at most intersections.
Google-address: 8920 US-14, Eyota, MN 55934, USA

Name: Eastwood Golf Course
Notes: The main training course in Rochester. Usually groomed regularly it can get a bit hardpacked between snowfalls.
Google-address: Towne Club Pkwy SE, Rochester, MN 55904, USA

Name: Soldier's Field Golf Course
Notes: Nice quiet trails right in the city on the golf course. With the city light you can see the trails fairly well at night.
Google-address: 244 Soldiers Field Dr SW, Rochester, MN 55902, USA

Name: Great River Bluffs State Park
Notes: Trails rated easy to moderate.
Google-address: Kipp Dr, Winona, MN 55987, USA

Name: Lindenwood Park Ski Trails
Notes: A flat trail that follows the Red River of the North along its floodplain. 10km groomed for classical 4km for skating.
Google-address: 203 22nd Ave S, Moorhead, MN 56560, USA

Name: Saint Mary's University
Notes: Some of the best trails in southern Minnesota. Tucked in the valley behind the school the trails run around the northern slopes of the valley making them quite challenging and also well protected from the sun. Some lighted sections and snowmaking operations.
Google-address: 740 Terrace Heights, Winona, MN 55987, USA

Name: Balsam Branch Trails
Notes: The Balsam Branch trails are open to the public for no charge. When there is snow tracks are set by Polk County Park and volunteers. The trailhead parking area is always well plowed. Toilet facilities are available at the nearby Kennedy Environmental center but no coffee shop or warming facility. Roughly 4K of lighted trails added in 2010.
Google-address: 1392 120th Ave, Amery, WI 54001, USA

Name: Ashland Ski Trail
Notes: A beautiful trail right in the city of Ashland. The full 6.3 kilometers of the trail are tracked for classic style skiing and most are groomed for skate style skiing as well.
Google-address: 1635 Maple Ln, Ashland, WI 54806, USA

Name: Mt. Ashwabay Ski Trails
Notes: A great mix of beginner and expert ski trails. With the inclusion of the Jerry Jolly Trails there is about 25 km groomed for skating and classic. There is also an additional 15 km of classic only trails. With views of Lake Superior and the Apostle Islands this is a very scenic area to ski. There is a nice lodge which sells snacks and food as well as a ski patrol and small downhill area.
Google-address: 32515 Ski Hill Rd, Bayfield, WI 54814, USA

Name: Blue Hills Trail
Notes: A 32K network of well-signed trails coursing through heavily wooded hills and valleys. Timely grooming for both skating and striding. Heated log warming house toilets and ample parking.
Google-address: Fire Lane Rd, Weyerhaeuser, WI 54895, USA

Name: After Hours Ski Trail
Notes: Mostly easy to moderate with a few challenging hills. Best known for good grooming and scenic views of the Brule River. Groomed for both classic and skating. Home to the River View Loppet Race in March.
Google-address: 5750 Afterhours Rd, Brule, WI 54820, USA

Name: Telemark Resort Trails
Notes: Some of the most famous trails in the area! The American Birkie starts here and the Korteloppet makes extensive use of the trail system.
Google-address: Telemark Rd, Cable, WI 54821, USA

Name: Anvil National Recreation Trail
Notes: Forested terrain varies from mostly level (West Trail East Trail) to rolling hills (Ninemile Trail Lake Loop) to hilly (Devil's Run). Chickadees waiting to eat birdseed from your hand at the warming shelter. Toilets are available at the parking area and warming shelter.
Google-address: 2511 WI-70, Eagle River, WI 54521, USA

Name: Nicolet North Trail
Notes: Forested terrain varies from nearly level (Ash Meadow Camp 22) to mostly rolling (Roller Coaster Run The Gulch Pat Shay Trail Narrow Gauge Loop) to several scattered hills. This trail connects with the Anvil National Recreation Trail.
Google-address: Fournier Rd, Three Lakes, WI 54562, USA

Name: Nordmarka Ski Trails
Notes: This trail is maintained by the Nordmarka Ski Club of Eagle River.
Google-address: 504 McKinley Blvd, Eagle River, WI 54521, USA

Name: Edgewood Golf Course Ski Trail
Notes: Classical trails wind through this golf course situated on the floodplain of the Red River of the North. Also 5K of skating trails.
Google-address: 3790 Aspyn Ln N, Fargo, ND 58102, USA

Name: Lake Forest Recreation Area
Notes: Part of the Lake Forest Recreation Area Golf Course.
Google-address: 3612 Eagle Waters Rd, Eagle River, WI 54521, USA

Name: Tower Ridge Ski Area
Notes: Great trails--hills and flats--for all levels. Groomed for both classical and skating. There are about 3km of lighted trails.
Google-address: 641 Co Rd L, Eau Claire, WI 54703, USA

Name: Birkie Trail
Notes: The famous Birkie trail. A great rolling trail through the woods between Cable and Hayward. There is a short section south at Hwy OO that is lighted. There are snowmaking trails at the Start area.
Google-address: 12205 County OO, Hayward, WI 54843, USA

Name: Willow River State Park
Notes: Trails range from easy such as the Purple Trail running along the Willow River to the challenging Brown and Silver trails. Trails are groomed for both classical and skate skiing. All grooming is done by volunteer groomers who pride themselves in providing the best possible conditions.
Google-address: 1034 Co Hwy A, Hudson, WI 54016, USA

Name: Hixon Forest
Notes: The trails are groomed by the City of La Crosse Park Department after each snowfall. They are groomed for skate-skiing and classic skiing.
Google-address: Unnamed Road, La Crosse, WI 54601, USA

Name: Hoffman Hills
Notes: Challenging trails located 10 miles NE of Menomonie.
Google-address: 730th St, Menomonie, WI 54751, USA

Name: Red Cedar River Trail
Notes: A groomed stretch from Menomonie to Downsville. Red Cedar Outfitters offer return van rides for a one-way ski trip. Follow direction signs from I-94.
Google-address: 912 Brickyard Road,, Menomonie, WI 54751, USA

Name: Mecca
Notes: Trails are on rolling glacial terrain through pine spruce and tamarack forests. A heated chalet with a vault toilet wax bench and changing room is located at the Cabin trailhead. There is a second trailhead at the Little Turtle Flowage parking lot.
Google-address: 4686N Fierick Rd, Mercer, WI 54547, USA

Name: Minocqua Winter Park Nordic Center
Notes: PistenBully groomed trails (with 12 km groomed for classic-only) 2 km lighted and 15km of power-tilled single-track ski trails. Glaciated terrain provides for a wide range of beginner to expert level trails and a telemark slope. On-site amenities include a chalet with PSIA certified ski school and& ski shop food service and a heated waxing room.
Google-address: 12372 Scotchman Lake Rd, Minocqua, WI 54548, USA

Name: Montreal Trails
Notes: 2km railroad grade makes for great cruising. Other steeper plunges down to the grade. Trails are in the city of Montreal just west of Ironwood/Hurley. Densely wooded and secluded. Donation box. Connects with 19km Uller trail to Whitecap Mtn which is even more remote.
Google-address: 6 Bessemer St, Montreal, WI 54550, USA

Name: Levis/Trow Mound Trail
Notes: The trail system consists of approximately fifteen miles of groomed trail and another ten of ungroomed backcountry routes. The more advanced trails are located north and west of Levis on Trow Mound while intermediate and easy trails lay near the base of Levis Mound. All groomed trails are set with diagonal tracks and a skating lane averaging 12 feet wide. Depending on snow conditions the trail is generally groomed twice per week. Trail passes are required. Facilities include a new cross-country ski chalet running water mens and womens bathrooms.
Google-address: WI-95, Neillsville, WI 54456, USA

Name: Afterglow Lake Resort
Notes: Afterglow Ski Trails are groomed for skate and classic 5-7 times a week with a Tidd Tech G2. The full width groomed trails are protected by a thick mixed hardwood forest with trees right to the trails edge. A large heated warm up room is perfect to wait for the diehards in your group. UP snowbelt for reliable snow.
Google-address: 4945 Sugar Maple Rd, Phelps, WI 54554, USA

Name: Timberland Hills
Notes: A great trail system! Nice wide trails and many challenging sections.
Google-address: 1832 Boyd Ln, Barronett, WI 54813, USA

Name: Timberland Hills West
Notes: Right next door to the famous Timberland Hills trails this is a short section that is lighted until around 11 pm.
Google-address: 2993 3rd St, Barronett, WI 54813, USA

Name: Razorback Ridges Trail
Notes: Mixed forest and open field terrain varies from nearly level to mostly hilly with several scattered hills. All 18 trail segments are groomed and only 2 segments groomed exclusively for classical. McKay's Corner Store located at the trailhead offers warming shelter food and beverages.
Google-address: 3110 Razorback Rd, Sayner, WI 54560, USA

Name: Plover River Ski Trail
Notes: Mostly wooded terrain along segments of Plover River. Warming shelter open on weekends. Located off Hwy 66 east of Stevens Point past the airport; turn right at Plover River Trail sign.
Google-address: 5294 Airport Rd, Stevens Point, WI 54482, USA

Name: Superior Municipal Forest
Notes: Trails groomed for classical and skate skiing. Trail fee required.
Google-address: 3509 N 28th St, Superior, WI 54880, USA

Name: Nine Mile County Forest Recreation Area
Notes: One of the top trails in NE Wisconsin. Trails are generally one-way and double-tracked (skate and classic). The ski chalet offers a changing area ski and snowshoe equipment rentals daily and annual trail passes and restrooms. There roughly 6K of lighted trails and programmed to go on at dusk until 9 pm. Trail difficulty ranges from beginner to difficult.
Google-address: 221700 Red Bud Rd, Wausau, WI 54401, USA

Name: Hiram Ski Trail
Notes: Another set of trails within the Foot Hills State Forest these are rated from novice to expert.
Google-address: 6405 Lower 10 Mile Lake Rd NW, Hackensack, MN 56452, USA

Name: Sylvan Hill Park
Notes: Rated beginner to intermediate. The trails are hilly and wooded and meander through Sylvan Hill Park. Parking is available in the Sylvan Chalet parking lot.
Google-address: 1001 N 10th St, Wausau, WI 54403, USA

Name: Greenwood Hills Trail
Notes: This trail is located on hilly terrain just east of the Wausau City limits on Greenwood Hills Golf Course. This golf course skiing provides challenging climbs and exhilarating downhills. The trail includes wooded sections.
Google-address: 2002 Poplar Ln, Wausau, WI 54403, USA

Name: ABR
Notes: ABR is a full service touring center located on scenic and varied terrain along the Montreal River in Ironwood Michigan. Trailhead cabin retail ski shop rentals and lessons available. They have state of the art grooming equipment including Pisten Bully powertillers and groom daily. Open at 9 AM daily from November to April 1st.
Google-address: N8934 S Range Rd, Ironwood, MI 49938, USA

Name: Swedetown Trails
Notes: Beginner to expert trails. 4.5k lighted until 10 p.m. Host to the annual Great Bear Chase. Up down turns mixed stands of forest and clearings provide an exciting terrain for the skier. The flow of the trail is Swedetown's specialty. The trail is meticulously groomed and the addition of a warming chalet and lighted trail have made Swedetown hard to beat.
Google-address: 25196 Bridge St, Calumet, MI 49913, USA

Name: Chassell Trail
Notes: Easy to intermediate level. The hills have been designed to provide ample landing space at the bottom with no surprise corners. 1km lighted trail. Maintained through cooperation from private landholders and The Chassell Recreation Club on a volunteer basis. Parking and the trailhead at the Chassell Heritage Center.
Google-address: 42403 Wilson Memorial Dr, Chassell, MI 49916, USA

Name: Copper Harbor Pathway
Notes: Trails vary from easy to expert including the Kamakazie 9 km Intermediate to Expert loop.
Google-address: Fanny Hoe Creek, Mohawk, MI 49950, USA

Name: Maasto Hiihto Ski Trails
Notes: The trail is located in the city of Hancock and can be accessed from many points. The main trailhead is located at the Houghton County Arena. Easy to expert trails pass a picnic spot and beautiful vistas.
Google-address: 1500 Birch St, Hancock, MI 49930, USA

Name: Michigan Tech University Ski Trails
Notes: Long downhills gathering speed and sharp turns at the bottom are distinctive of the trails you will find here. 34k of groomed trails 24k of skate trails 7k lighted trails in the evening until 9pm. Trails are groomed daily to manage the 200"+ of annual snowfall. Heated chalets at the Main Trailhead and Nara Trailhead.
Google-address: Core loop, Houghton, MI 49931, USA

Name: Deep Portage Ski Trails
Notes: Located in the Deep Portage Conservation Reserve the trails are rated novice to expert.
Google-address: 2197 Nature Center Dr NW, Hackensack, MN 56452, USA

Name: Hill Street Classic Trails
Notes: Trails range from easy to difficult. Part of the Superior Nordic Training and Recreation Area. Located directly west of Suicide Bowl Trails.

Name: National Mine Ski Area
Notes: Just west of Ishpeming these trails also have a biathlon range.
Google-address: Co Rd PC, Negaunee, MI 49866, USA

Name: Porcupine Mountains Wilderness State Park
Notes: Enjoy the quiet splendor of wooded trails and breathtaking vistas blanketed in winter white from any of the Porkies cross-country trails. A unique one-ride lift ticket provides a quick access to the heart of the Nordic trail system from the Chalet.

Name: Blueberry Ridge Trail
Notes: Part of the DNR Forest with a 2.7km lighted loop. Trails range from easy to advanced with some classical-only trails.

Name: Twin Lakes State Park
Notes: Easy to moderate trails provide a view of Lake Superior at the scenic overlook sight. All trails are maintained on a volunteer effort. Parking and the trailhead are at the DNR Field Office.

Name: Macbride Nature Recreation Area
Notes: The trails are mostly wide and gentle with about 4 km of very challenging terrain. The system is groomed weekly or after a snowfall.
Google-address: 2095 Mehaffey Bridge Rd NE, Solon, IA 52333

Name: Lake Bronson State Park
Notes: Trails are rated easy. The park plans to add 2.3 more miles of trail to the system for winter 2000-2001.

Name: Itasca State Park
Notes: Here you will find the Headwaters to the Mississippi amongst towering pines. Trails are easy to difficult.
Google-address: 36750 Main Park Dr, Park Rapids, MN 56470, USA

Name: Soaring Eagle Trail
Notes: Groomed classical/skate trails wind through a varied forest ranging from baby aspen to mature balsam and pine. Trails vary from easy to advanced. There is also a one-mile blazed showshoe trail warming house and outdoor toilet.

Name: Three Island Park
Notes: This is an area of exceptional beauty with trails winding along Three Island Lake and Turtle River.

Name: Cut Lake Ski Trail
Notes: Located in the Foot Hills State Forest the trails are rated from novice to expert.

Name: Shingobee Recreation Area Trails
Notes: Running along the slopes of the Shingobee River Valley of the Chippewa National Forest these are rated from novice to expert. 3k are now being groomed for skating.

Name: Zippel Bay State Park
Notes: 6K groomed for skating and about 12K groomed for classic. Trails are definately beginner friendly and pass through a variety of forest types including jack pine birch aspen spruce-balsam and some low-land brush. One section passes through an old gravel pit.

Name: Andes Tower Hill Ski Area
Notes: Nice variety of terrain on mostly wooded trails adjacent to commercial ski area. Both classical and skating tracks. On some Saturdays breakfast is served at a warming house halfway down the trail--call for availability. 1.5km lighted.

Name: Glendalough State Park
Notes: One of the last large tracts of undeveloped lakeshore in western Minnesota (9.2 miles) lies within the park. The gently rolling topography is an excellent example of original landscape transition from prairie to northern hardwoods. This hilly lake-strewn and partially wooded countryside is an excellent setting for x-country skiing. Most trails are fairly level and easy to ski.
Google-address: Co Rd 16, Battle Lake, MN 56515, USA

Name: Pine Beach Trail
Notes: Cragun's has upgrade the grooming in recent years. Connects with Legacy Trails.
Google-address: 1664 Pine Beach Rd, East Gull Lake, MN 56401, USA

Name: Northland Arboretum
Notes: Nice winding trails the Arboretum trails are rated beginner to moderate and are located right in Brainerd. Nearly 5K of the trails are lighted.
Google-address: 603 Cir Pines Dr, Brainerd, MN 56401, USA

Name: French Rapids Ski Trails
Notes: Some incredible climbs and descents. Offers stunning views of the Mississippi River. Mainly expert trails.
Google-address: 17098 County Rd 142 NE, Brainerd, MN 56401, USA

Name: Crow Wing State Park
Notes: Nice trails through the woods along the Mississippi River. Novice to Intermediate.
Google-address: State Park Rd, Brainerd, MN 56401, USA

Name: Buena Vista Ski Trail
Notes: Home course for the Minnesota Finlandia and Snowjourn races. It's a great course with lots of ups and downs and mainly in the woods.
Google-address: 19635 Irvine Ave NW, Bemidji, MN 56601, USA

Name: Spidahl Ski Gaard
Notes: Spidahl Ski Gard (farm in Norsk) is a private touring center located in sugar maple hills four miles south of Maplewood State Park. It has trails groomed for classical and skate skiing with ski and snowshoe rentals available. The owners Cindy and David Spidahl love to ski and it shows in the trail layout and grooming.

Name: Lutsen Mountains Nordic Trails
Notes: Ski trails are located around the downhill slopes and are accessible by gondola and chair lifts. Your Nordic Center ticket allows you to ride the lifts up the mountains and then gradually descend groomed tracked trails into the Poplar River valley through a mixed forest of aspen birch maples and evergreens.
Google-address: 445 Ski Hill Rd, Lutsen, MN 55612, USA

Name: Lake Carlos State Park
Notes: Classic-only trails are moderate in difficulty and cover rolling terrain.
Google-address: 2630 County Rd 38 NE, Alexandria, MN 56308, USA

Name: Wolverine Ski Trail
Notes: Trails consist of 5 separate loops groomed by volunteers from the Wolverine Nordic Ski Club. An interesting mix for all ability levels. Heavily wooded terrain and great snow make for a wonderful ski experience.New warming shelter.
Google-address: 6034 Sunset Rd, Ironwood, MI 49938, USA

Name: Cleary Lake Regional Park
Notes: Trails range from beginner to intermediate level. 6.8km of the trails are lighted daily until 10 p.m..
Google-address: 18110 Cleary Lake Ct NE, Prior Lake, MN 55372, USA

Name: Montebello Trail
Notes: Located in the heart of the city of Bemidji close to many hotels and restaurants. Two km of lighted track. Ideal trail for beginners.

Name: George Wyth State Park
Notes: Trails are primarily flat and run over bike paths as well as hiking paths. Groomed for skating and classic.
Google-address: 2626 Wyth Rd, Waterloo, IA 50703, USA

Name: Pine Valley
Notes: Excellent trail with challenging terrain. It has difficult climbs as well as gradual rolling sections. Part of the system is lit from 4:30 to 9:30 all winter. Located adjacent to Cloquet area recreation center (hockey rink) south of Pine Tree Plaza.

Name: Warner Lake Park
Notes: The 3.5 miles of trails loop through beautiful hardwood and pines and around the lake. Trail segments for all abilities.

Name: Quarry Park and Nature Preserve
Notes: The 4.2 miles of trails loop through trees wetlands prairies and past granite quarries and rock remnants. Trails are rated Easy and Intermediate. Parts of the trails are groomed for skate skiing along with the classic. Check out the four miles of lighted trails.

Name: Milaca Trails
Notes: The city of Milaca trails are single tracked and groomed for traditional skiiing. These trails are open to mountain biking (12 mi.) in the non-snow season.
Google-address: 303 3rd Ave SW, Milaca, MN 56353, USA

Name: Mississippi River County Park
Notes: The 3.5 miles of trails loop through pines and hardwood forest and offer beautiful views of the Mississippi River. The trails are rated as easy.
Google-address: 41300 Co Rd 1, Rice, MN 56367, USA

Name: Rock Lake
Notes: This is a system of classic-only trails made up of ever increasing inter-connected loops through some of the loveliest country in the Midwest. Very hilly -- intermediate to advanced skills recommended.
Google-address: 21163 Co Hwy M, Cable, WI 54821, USA

Name: Mukwonago Trail
Notes: A beautiful challenging system of loops located about 17 miles east of Hayward. Trails are for intermediate to advanced skill levels and offer a great "in the woods" skiing experience.
Google-address: WI-77, Hayward, WI 54843, USA

Name: Pine Point Park
Notes: Small park near the end of the Gateway Trail. There is beautiful scenery with trails winding through pine forest and near small lakes and picturesque farms. The course is quiet sheltered and has a lot of fun roling hills. Most of the terrain is intermediate in difficulty.
Google-address: 11880 Norell Ave N, Stillwater, MN 55082, USA

Name: Nordic Woods
Notes: Mostly intermediate level trails are groomed for classical or both classic and skating. There is also a beginner loop. Skating sections tend to be quite narrow and the trail is remote and heavily wooded. Ideal classical terrain.
Google-address: Dubois Rd, Spooner, WI 54801, USA

Name: North Lakeland Discovery Center
Notes: The terrain is gentle and winds through the woods along the lake bog and nearby Manitowish River. There is also a warming/changing room with free hot apple cider and cookies. Trails are maintained by volunteers at the Discovery Center.
Google-address: 14006 Discovery Ln, Manitowish Waters, WI 54545, USA

Name: Black River Falls State Forest
Notes: Some of the finest ski-touring trails in Wisconsin. Parking can be found at the Wildcat Lot about 4 miles NE of Millston and at Smrekar Lot about 4 miles east of Millston. Trails run through woodlands and rolling terrain. There are 9 loops totaling 24 miles and most trails are designated one-way. Ridge Norway Pine and Wildcat trails have very steep sections and are recommended for experts.
Google-address: North Settlement Road, Warrens, WI 54666, USA

Name: Lake Maria State Park
Notes: Beginner to intermediate skill level primarily intermediate. Rolling terrain goes through wooded areas old growth forest areas and past lakes and ponds.
Google-address: 11508 Clementa Ave NW, Monticello, MN 55362, USA

Name: Collinwood Park
Notes: 4 miles of classic groomed trails. Intermediate level. Trails go through woods and open grass lands view of Collinwood Lake and wetlands. Deer turkey and pheasants are likely to be seen.
Google-address: 17251 70th St SW, Cokato, MN 55321, USA

Name: Montissippi Park
Notes: Two miles of classic groomed trails. These trails are set on a paved trail. Flat trails through a pine plantation next to the Mississippi River. Good for first time or beginner skiers.
Google-address: 2807 County Rd 75 NE, Monticello, MN 55362, USA

Name: Otsego Park
Notes: 1.5 miles of classic groomed trails. Trail overlooks Mississippi River woods and native prairie. Good for beginners.
Google-address: 15186 96th St NE, Otsego, MN 55330, USA

Name: Stanley Eddy Park Reserve
Notes: Two units with a combined 7.5 miles of trail. Trail is very hilly excellent big woods environment. Experienced skiers.
Google-address: 5278 Co Hwy 2, South Haven, MN 55382, USA

Name: Robert Ney Regional Park
Notes: 3.5 miles of classic groomed trails. Marshes and forest canopy excellent area to view wildlife. Intermediate skiers will enjoy this park. With small hills and flat areas it is an excellent destination.
Google-address: 5488 73rd St NW, Maple Lake, MN 55358, USA

Name: Harry Larson County Forest
Notes: Two miles of classic groomed trails. Just North of Lake Maria State Park this is and excellent warm up. With rolling terrain mature oak forest with pockets of big tooth aspen this is primarily for the intermediate skiers.
Google-address: 12700 Clementa Ave NW, Monticello, MN 55362, USA

Name: Kaplan's Woods Parkway
Notes: Multi-use trail with 7 km of trails in hardwood forest and 3 km adjacent along bikeway lit for night skiing. Ravine terrain provides challenging hills. Wide trails suitable for skating tracked for classic when snow is sufficient.
Google-address: 1120 18th St SW, Owatonna, MN 55060, USA

Name: Hickory Ridge Trail
Notes: This trail winds through quiet and scenic oak and aspen forests. All loops are challenging to the skier with rolling to steep grades. All loops are signed with either a snowflake blazer or a blazer depicting a skier complete with kilometer markings. Ski trail rest shelters are located at the North and South loops. The entire system is groomed for both traditional and skate skiing. No dogs permitted.
Google-address: 16771 225th Ave, Bloomer, WI 54724, USA

Name: Giants Ridge
Notes: A system intially developed for intensive training by the USSA Ski Team presents long gradual grades spectacular vistas and roller coaster rides and a variety of challenges for beginners through accomplished skiers. Trails weave through the Superior National Forest.
Google-address: 6329 Wynne Creek Dr, Biwabik, MN 55708, USA

Name: Eagle Lake Regional Park
Notes: The trail is located about two blocks West of Hwy 169 on Bass Lake Rd. Overall this is a nice little gem. The terrain is very gentle and seems an ideal place for a family with small children or beginner skiers.
Google-address: 10840 57th Ave N, Minneapolis, MN 55442, USA

Name: East River Valley Park/Carr's Woods
Notes: Nearly level trail through densely wooded flood plain. This trail is one of the best in Iowa because of the protection afforded by the dense tree cover. Trail is groomed for classic and skating on Fridays by local enthusiasts.
Google-address: Ames, IA 50010

Name: Sister's Farm
Notes: Growing from a few classical trails this area now includes a fine skate trail that parallels the Flambeau River. Classical trails on west side skate east side.
Google-address: 4058-4360 Sisters Farm Rd, Ladysmith, WI 54848

Name: Iowa State University Cross County Course
Notes: This one of only two or three trail systems in the US that is dedicated to cross country running. The trail winds along College Creek in the wooded ISU Arboretuem and out into open fields. It has moderately rolling terrain with several challenging hills. The trail has very good turf cover but unfortunately is not groomed regularly. Usually there is a classic track established by local use. Skating can be great on this trail if the snow conditions are right.
Google-address: Ames, IA

Name: Ellis Park
Notes: Classic grooming on the very rolling hills of Ellis Park Golf Course. Best trails within the city limits.
